<subSubSection id="0E1FE0F3C64725A27FF1AF14ADB544AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph id="F90AAD5CAD222001379C3E592BA2C4F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="C5BB8E95F985C8BF7CF4D5230AD88674" authority="Lonsdale, 2014" authorityName="Lonsdale" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Euhexomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Euhexomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C06004934DFE3D96E2F1C8096A05F159" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Euhexomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="34A57087A7CE330083D1DD4F00B95C42" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="481 - 513" refId="B140" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2014. Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 146 (5): 481 - 513, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" title="Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" volume="146" year="2014">Lonsdale (2014)</bibRefCitation>
for a lineage of mostly north-temperate 
<taxonomicName id="60F0B28314ECB902E92559306B833566" authority="Lonsdale, 2014" authorityName="Lonsdale" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Salicaceae" genus="Euhexomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Salicaceae</taxonomicName>
-feeding species where the larva forms an ovate gall in the cortex of a twig. These species were previously treated as part of 
<taxonomicName id="6437E1ED61C340D34C4C2E8D3F665A40" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1936" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Hexomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hexomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="109B5CD2190CCCD56541370367294148" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hexomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Enderlein, but 
<bibRefCitation id="DA33AF180E0C553B489D5A99DDE2AFE3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="481 - 513" refId="B140" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2014. Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 146 (5): 481 - 513, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" title="Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" volume="146" year="2014">Lonsdale (2014)</bibRefCitation>
found the genus to be a polyphyletic dumping ground for a miscellany of gall-forming species, with the morphologically disparate type species belonging to 
<taxonomicName id="3001388C2E5DBFB15B8CB8B6DEE5B4C3" authorityName="Braschnikov" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="169640974980C9E9290D02230B9EEB58" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He subsequently included the name 
<taxonomicName id="EF1F174ED50FD6BF79D16B0C2498938C" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1936" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Hexomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hexomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="039E3D400DE0EE7F823ADC15DE10140F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hexomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="F8BEEE576DB5942593CB8FE466FC87AF" authorityName="Braschnikov" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BA19C6BA650D2D559AF6141B2A59106A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B021931588842146EFCC8BDD23611A6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Species are brown and non-metallic (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DA40302A083F0154E120F20AAB520CEC" captionStart="Figures 37–44" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 37 - 44. 37 Agromyza aristata Malloch, female lateral 38 Agromyza bispinata Spencer, female lateral with detail of stridulatory file 39, 40 Agromyza kincaidi Malloch, male head (arrow indicates discrete apical tuft of hairs) 39 lateral 40 same, anterior 41, 42 Agromyza bispinata, male head 41 lateral 42 same, anterior 43 Agromyza sp., female (S. A. Marshall - Ontario, Hornings Mills) 44 Euhexomyza schineri (Giraud) (T. Murray - Massachusetts, Groton)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figures37-44" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572104" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">44</figureCitation>
), they have a rounded clypeus and lack a prescutellar acrostichal. The fronto-orbital plate and parafacial are pronounced, forming a strong ring around the eye, the postsutural intra-alars are subequal (anterior seta never strong), and only the mid tibia sometimes has a lateromedial seta. The male genitalia (at least of the north temperate 
<taxonomicName id="6EEA78B47192283772DD382F575C72FB" authorityName="Braschnikov" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Salicaceae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Salicaceae</taxonomicName>
-feeders) are typified by a distiphallus that has the base broad and rounded and the apex tapered, and the phallophorus has a unique ventral 
<normalizedToken id="AD41C591E1A776F480B7F8244CC82F4B" originalValue="“pouch”">&quot;pouch&quot;</normalizedToken>
emerging from the distal margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C87CB159586ED5A6C643A34248613A40" captionStart="Figure 250" captionStartId="F38" captionText="Figure 250. Euhexomyza albicula (Spencer), male holotype genitalia, with phallus (broken off) inset at right, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figure250" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572137" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">250</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="27B670E698E00637D58B7750DB79FD38" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="481 - 513" refId="B140" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2014. Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 146 (5): 481 - 513, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" title="Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2014.2" volume="146" year="2014">Lonsdale 2014</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 62).
</paragraph>
